ce:section.ce:para:
This study aims at a rational design strategy that combines the synthesis of CD with specific properties and their applications for nanopesticides, water purification, and theranostic treatment (Table 1
                     ). One of the critical problems of CD in these applications is to enhance the high-quality intrinsic properties of CD, including water solubility, stability, and intensity of fluorescence. Therefore, we proposed a conceptual design approach to address these problems and achieve these desired properties, targeting to create CD with the required modification of bulk/size, surface, and morphology of CD (Fig. 1
                     ). Based on the literature, the size of CD from 2 to 3 nm exhibits an excellent photocatalytic activity [24]. In addition, it has been reported that carbon quantum dots have a spherical morphology with quantum confinement and high crystal structure [25], which exhibit a stable system in an aqueous solution. Besides, heteroatom doping is one of the most effective approaches for modulating CD's bulk/size, surface, and morphology [26]. It is revealed that the photoluminescence of CD was enhanced by introducing amide (-NH2) functional groups into the surface [27]. A synergistic effect of graphitic N and pyrrolic N in graphene for the enhanced photocatalytic performance of CD is confirmed [28]. In addition, for improved water solubility and stability, introducing –OH and –COOH functional groups on the surface of CD is one of the easiest and most effective strategies [29,30].

In scenario 1 (Fig. 12a), at a zeta potential of ±5 mV, the electrical double layer interactions (V
                           D
                        ) were lower than 0.05 and reached 0 at the distance of 3 nm, while the energy force of van der Waals interactions (VH) was by far higher than that of VD. As a result, when increasing the distance from 0 to 10 nm, NCQD’ total energy force (VT) was below 0, indicating a tendency to congregate NCQD in an aqueous solution. This result was explained that in NCQD, there was a lack of functional groups (-NH2 and –OH) on the surface leading to low absorption of water molecules to form the electrical double layers. In other words, NCQD interacted majorly via van der Waals interactions, resulting in a tendency to aggregation.
